
[1]cushion

   CUSHION, n.

   1. A pillow for a seat; a soft pad to be placed on a chair; a bag,
   stuffed with wool, hair or other soft material.

   2. A bag of leather filled with sand, used by engravers to support the
   plate.

   3. In gilding, a stuffing of fine tow or wool, covered by leather, on a
   board; used for receiving the leaves of gold from the paper, in order
   to its being cut into proper sizes and figures.

   Ladys cushion, a plant, a species of saxifraga.

   Sea cushion, sea pink or thrift, a species of Statice.

                     CUSHION, v.t. To seat on a cushion.
